'''Vladimír Coufal''' ({{IPA|cs|ˈvlaɟɪmiːr ˈtsoufal}}; born 22 August 1992) is a Czech professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]] for German {{German football updater|Hoffenhe}} club [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]] and the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]].

He has previously played for Bílovec, [[FC Hlučín|Hlučín]], [[SFC Opava|Opava]], [[FC Slovan Liberec|Slovan Liberec]], [[SK Slavia Praha|Slavia Prague]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].

Coufal made his senior debut for the Czech Republic in November 2017, and has gone on to make over 50 appearances, scoring two goals.

==Club career==
Coufal began his career at local club [[FC Baník Ostrava|Baník Ostrava]], playing in the club's academy, before being released at the age of 17 as he was considered to be too small.<ref name=telegraph1>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2022/04/23/rise-vladimir-coufal-escaped-playing-sausages-beer-find-home/|title=The rise of Vladimir Coufal: 'How I escaped playing for sausages and beer to find my home at West Ham'|first=Mike|last=McGrath|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 April 2022}}</ref> In 2009, following his release from Baník Ostrava, Coufal joined amateur club ŠSK Bílovec. He believed Baník had destroyed his opportunity to become a professional footballer and described his time with Bílovec as playing "with 40-year-old men. These guys played for sausages and beer after the game, just to drink after work".<ref name=telegraph1/><ref name = "Times">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/if-you-dont-have-a-broken-leg-you-can-play-west-hams-new-psycho-vladimir-coufal-ready-for-wales-test-b3kv63jqx|title='If you don't have a broken leg, you can play' – West Ham's new 'psycho' Vladimir Coufal ready for Wales test|date=29 March 2021|access-date=24 February 2022|work=[[The Times]]}}</ref>

===Hlučín===
Coufal began his professional career with [[FC Hlučín|Hlučín]], making his debut against [[Dukla Prague]] in September 2010 in [[Czech National Football League|2. Liga]] just after his 18th birthday.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|title=West Ham United sign Czech Republic international Vladimír Coufal {{!}} West Ham United|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/october/02-october/west-ham-united-sign-czech-republic-international-vladimir|access-date=18 October 2020|publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref> During the 2010–11 season, Coufal made 14 appearances for the club.<ref name=":1" />

====Loan to Opava====
Coufal spent the 2011–12 season on loan with 2. Liga club [[SFC Opava|Opava]] where he made 13 appearances and scored one goal for the club.<ref name=":1" />

===Slovan Liberec===
After impressing in the second division with Hlučín and Opava, Coufal was signed by [[Czech First League]] club [[Slovan Liberec]] in 2012, following a trial with [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]], who saw Coufal as a replacement for the outgoing [[Ondřej Kušnír]], who had joined Liberec himself in the summer of 2012. Despite playing for Sparta Prague in a pre-season [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[FK Viktoria Žižkov|Viktoria Žižkov]], Sparta opted to sign [[Pablo Gil]] over Coufal.<ref name = "Expres">{{cite web|url=https://www.expres.cz/sport/vladimir-coufal-prestup-sparta-slavia.A180605_170035_dx-sport_lare|title=Před šesti lety nebyl Coufal pro Spartu dost dobrý, teď jí to vrátil i s úroky|date=5 June 2018|accessdate=24 February 2022|publisher=Expres|language=cs}}</ref>

During his first season with Liberec, Coufal played in ten league games.<ref name=":1" /> In his second season with the team, the [[2013–14 Czech First League|2013–14 season]], Coufal became a regular for the team featuring in 26 matches.<ref name=":1" /> Over the next three seasons, Coufal played consistently, making 88 appearances all competitions.<ref name=":1" />

Coufal's last season for Liberec was arguably his most impressive as he made 33 appearances across all competitions, scoring two goals. These performances also earned him a call up and debut to the Czech national team.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" /> Coufal was with Slovan Liberec for six seasons, making more than 150 appearances across all competitions, and playing in the team which won the [[2014–15 Czech Cup|Czech Cup in 2015]].<ref name="signed" /> During Coufal's time at Liberec, he was made club captain.<ref name="Times" />

===Slavia Prague===
Coufal's impressive displays at Slovan Liberec earned him a move to one of the Czech Republic's largest clubs, [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]], following protracted interest from [[Prague derby|rivals]] Sparta Prague. On 1 July 2018, Coufal joined Slavia Prague on a three-year contract, for a reported fee of 18 million [[Czech koruna|Kč]]. Upon his move to Slavia Prague, Coufal was reunited with manager [[Jindřich Trpišovský]], who he had previously played under at Slovan Liberec.<ref name="Expres" />

During the [[2018–19 Czech First League|2018–19 season]], Coufal made 39 appearances for Slavia Prague, scoring 4 goals and helping lead the team to the [[Czech First League]] title.<ref name=":1" /> The next season, during the [[2019–20 Czech First League|2019–20 campaign]], he made 42 appearances and scored three goals in a season that was suspended for two months due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the Czech Republic|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name=":1" /> During this season, Coufal and Slavia Prague retained the Czech First League title. During the [[2020–21 Czech First League|2020–21 season]], Coufal made a final seven appearances for Slavia Prague before transferring to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and the [[Premier League]],<ref name=":0" /> playing his last game for the club in a 4–1 [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification loss against Danish club [[FC Midtjylland|Midtjylland]].<ref name = "Bez">{{cite web|url=https://www.bezfrazi.cz/pribehy/vladimir-coufal/bubliny-snu|title=Bubliny snů|accessdate=28 April 2022|publisher=Bez frází|language=cs}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
On 2 October 2020, Coufal joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for a fee of £5.4&nbsp;million, signing a three-year deal, reuniting with fellow Czech and former Slavia Prague teammate [[Tomáš Souček]],<ref name="signed">{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/october/02-october/west-ham-united-sign-czech-republic-international-vladimir|title=West Ham United sign Czech Republic international Vladimír Coufal|publisher=[[West Ham United F.C.]]|date=2 October 2020|access-date=2 October 2020}}</ref> following interest from fellow Premier League clubs [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref name = "Bez"/> He made his West Ham debut in a 3–0 win against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 4 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54313284|title=West Ham end Leicester's 100% winning start|work=BBC Sport |date=2 October 2020 }}</ref> Coufal created seven assists for West Ham during his [[2020–21 West Ham United F.C. season|first season]] in English football, one behind [[Aaron Cresswell]]. The pair created more assists than any other [[Premier League]] full-back duo in the [[2020–21 Premier League|2020–21 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/may/31-may/watch-every-aaron-cresswell-and-vladimir-coufal-assist-202021-season|title=Watch: Every Aaron Cresswell and Vladimír Coufal assist from the 2020/21 season|publisher=[[West Ham United F.C.]]|date=31 May 2021|access-date=13 July 2021}}</ref> Coufal finished runner-up in West Ham's [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] award for the 2020–21 season, behind compatriot Souček.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/august/06-august/west-ham-united-supporters-crown-tomas-soucek-202021-betway|title=West Ham United supporters crown Tomáš Souček 2020/21 Betway Hammer of the Year!|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=6 August 2021|access-date=6 August 2021}}</ref>

He achieved the [[UEFA Europa Conference League]] title with his club, featuring in a 2–1 victory over [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] in the [[2023 UEFA Europa Conference League final|final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/668521/west-ham-united-fiorentina |title=Fiorentina 1–2 West Ham United |publisher=ESPN |date=7 June 2023 }}</ref> On 9 May 2025, it was announced that Coufal would leave West Ham at the end of the [[2024–25 West Ham United F.C. season|2024–25 season]], after a five-year stay with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 May 2025 |title=Club Statement {{!}} Cresswell, Fabiański, Coufal and Ings to depart |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/club-statement-cresswell-fabianski-coufal-and-ings-depart |access-date=10 May 2025 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. }}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news |last=Thomas |first=Roshane |date=9 May 2025 |title=Aaron Cresswell, Lukasz Fabianski, Vladimir Coufal and Danny Ings to leave West Ham at end of season |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6344309/2025/05/09/west-ham-cresswell-fabianski-coufal-ings/ |access-date=10 May 2025 |work=[[The Athletic]] |language=en-GB |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In total, he made 180 appearances for West Ham.<ref name=":1" />

===TSG Hoffenheim===
On 5 August 2025, Coufal signed a one-year contract with [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]] in Germany as a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|url=https://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/aktuelles/news/2025/08/tsg-hoffenheim-verpflichtet-vladimir-coufal|title=TSG Hoffenheim verpflichtet Vladimir Coufal|trans-title=TSG Hoffenheim signs Vladimir Coufal|date=5 August 2025|access-date=5 August 2025|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ťalský|first=Štěpán|publisher=[[Mafra (company)|Mafra]]|url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/zahranici/vladimir-coufal-hoffenheim-prestup-kratkodoba-smlouva.A250805_152854_fot_zahranici_tals|title=Coufal je oficiálně hráčem Hoffenheimu. Smlouvu ale podepsal pouze na jeden rok|trans-title=Coufal is officially a Hoffenheim player. However, he only signed a one-year contract|date=5 August 2025|access-date=5 August 2025|language=cs|website=[[iDNES.cz]]}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Hoffenheim during the 4–1 loss against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on 20 September 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Law |first=James |date=20 September 2025 |title=Hoffenheim 1-4 Bayern Munich: Harry Kane hat-trick helps Bundesliga |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c7v17l63n72t |access-date=22 September 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==International career==
In 2014, Coufal made two appearances for the [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic under-21 side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://repre.fotbal.cz/hrac/hraci/4173|title=Vladimír Coufal|publisher=FAČR|accessdate=28 April 2022}}</ref>

Coufal debuted for the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]] on 11 November 2017 in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly match]] against [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite news|first1=Jan|last1=Palička|first2=Miloslav|last2=Novák|title=Oni snad nebyli ani zpocení, žasl debutant Coufal. Byl šťastný za výhru|trans-title="They might not be even sweaty", said debutant Coufal. He was happy to win.|url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/reprezentace/katar-cesko-priprava-dauha-mezistatni-utkani-rozhovor-coufal.A171111_202207_fot_reprez_min|website=[[Mladá fronta Dnes]]|location=Prague|publisher=[[Mafra (company)|Mafra]]|date=11 November 2017|language=cs}}</ref> On 4 September 2020, he scored his first goal for the Czech Republic, scoring the opening goal in a 3–1 [[UEFA Nations League]] group game against neighbours [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Čtenáři ocenili výkon na Slovensku, nejvíc je potěšil Coufal|url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/reprezentace/liga-narodu-uefa-slovensko-cesko-anketa-znamky-hodnoceni-ctenaru.A200905_142613_fot_reprez_vp2|website=Mladá fronta Dnes|location=Prague|publisher=Mafra|date=5 September 2020|language=cs}}</ref>

Coufal was a member of the Czech Republic squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]] which was eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/may/24-may/vladimir-coufal-and-tomas-soucek-called-czech-republic-uefa-euro-2020|title=Vladimír Coufal and Tomáš Souček called up by Czech Republic for UEFA Euro 2020|website=West Ham United|date=24 May 2021|access-date=4 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198684|title=Czech Republic 1–2 Denmark|website=BBC Sport|date=3 July 2021|access-date=4 July 2021}}</ref> On 16 November 2021, he served as captain for the first time, in a 2–0 [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualification]] game against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vladimír Coufal|url=https://www.bezfrazi.cz/podcasty/vladimir-coufal/vladimir-coufal-bez-frazi-plus|website=Bez frází|date=28 April 2022|language=cs}}</ref>

On 19 November 2023, Coufal along with [[Jakub Brabec]] and [[Jan Kuchta]] had been kicked out of the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] training camp after they allegedly went out [[Clubbing (subculture)|clubbing]] two days before the [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying Group E|Euro 2024 qualifier]] match against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Jacob|last=Leeks|title=West Ham star among three banished from national team after "fundamentally violating" rules|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/vladimir-coufal-czech-euro-2024-31476095|website=Mirror Online|date=19 November 2023|access-date=20 November 2023}}</ref> In May 2024, he was named to the Czech Republic squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Euro 2024: West Ham's Tomas Soucek and Vladimir Coufal in Czech squad |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c0jj1k74nwgo |access-date=28 May 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Coufal was born in the village of [[Ludgeřovice]]. Coufal's mother, [[Alena Dřevjaná]], represented the Czechoslovak gymnastic team at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]]. Coufal's siblings, [[Petr Coufal|Petr]] and Jana, are both [[Figure skating|figure skaters]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.denik.cz/fotbal-zajimavosti/fotbal-vladimir-coufal-ludgerovice-west-ham.html|title=V Baníku ho nechtěli, v Premier League Vladimír Coufal září|newspaper=Deník.cz |date=22 March 2021|accessdate=24 February 2022|publisher=Deník|language=cs |last1=Nohavica |first1=Jakub }}</ref>

